<h3>General FAQs<span class="heading-links" /></h3>
<h4><a name="gf1">What is Worklist?</a></h4>
<p>
    Worklist is High Fidelity's distributed development system.  Our global team
    of developers include Web Developers, Project Managers (Designers), Engineers, UI/UX experts and QA Testers.
</p>
<h4><a name="gf2">I'm a web programmer, can I work on Worklist?</a></h4>
<p>
    Absolutely! We're always looking for new talent to join our community. To get started,
    you'll need to have a <a href='https://github.com/'> Github </a>account. You can then <a href='https://worklist.net/'>
    Login</a> with your Github credentials.  On first time login, you'll be redirected to your settings page where we'll
    ask you to provide necessary Worklist account info.
</p>
<h4><a name="gf3">Why do I need a Github account?</a></h4>
<p>
    Worklist is completely federated with Github.  We require write access on repositories in order to create branches
    and pull requests from Worklist; for example, when you receive a bid acceptance on an Issue, a branch is created on
    your Github account under the Issue's ticket number. Later in the process, when you change the status of an Issue
    on Worklist to "Code Review," a pull request is automatically created from the Issue's branch.

Even private repo access is necessary as some of the code in the High Fidelity architecture is not public.
</p>
<h4><a name="gf4">What is an Issue?</a></h4>
<p>
    An Issue is equivalent to a job.
</p>

<h4><a name="gf5">What is the difference between a Developer and a Designer?</a></h4>
<p>
    Developer refers to the person performing the actual work on a Issue.  The Designer is the Issue Manager.
</p>
<h4><a name="gf6">What is a Bid?</a></h4>
<p>
    A bid is a Developer's proposal to perform work on an Issue.  Bids consist of 1) the amount you would like to be paid,
    2) the approach you will take to complete the work needed to resolve the Issue, 3) the amount of time that it will take
    to complete the work, and 4) how long you want the bid to remain active - the maximum time and our default is 7 days.
    <br/ > <br/ >
    When you enter a bid, it is always better to give a brief, yet detailed, description of how you intend to address
    the Issue requirements. Designers are not just looking for the lowest bid; we are looking for a considered bid that has
    some thought behind it while not being unrealistic in cost.
</p>
<h4><a name="gf7">What is a Fee?</a></h4>
<p>
    In addition to the initial bid, you will probably also see one or more fees attached to
    an Issue. During the course of an Issue, fees are added for code reviews(automatically calculated
    for most projects), testing or other help. We encourage Developers to use their best judgment
    when fee'ing in.
</p>

