<h4><a name="df3">What is the workflow of an Issue?</a></h4>
<p>Issues on Worklist go through various statuses from preparation through release. Once your bid is accepted,
you might find this cheat sheet helpful until you get the knack of our workflow.
<p><strong>Stage One: Preparation > Issue Setup</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Suggested -</strong> Worklist allows anyone to make suggestions for improvements to any active project. When
    Suggested issues are added, Designers are notified via email and they decide whether or not to move them into Bidding.</li>
    <li><strong>SuggestedWithBid -</strong> Sometimes when a Developer has a suggestion, they will also have a particular solution
    in mind and be willing to do the work. Once a Developer adds a Suggested issue, they have the ability to add a bid which in
    turn changes the status to SuggestedWithBid.  Designers are again notified and make the final decision on whether or not to go
    ahead with the issue.</li>
    <li><strong>Pass -</strong> If for some reason a Designer decides not to move an issue into Bidding, they will set the
    issue to Pass.  Issues in Suggested and SuggestedWithBid status are also auto-passed once they age 30 days.</li>
    <li><strong>Bidding -</strong> Once an Issue is set to Bidding by a Designer, any Developer can put in their offer.
    Designers will review bids and accept based upon the best match to the issue requirements.</li>
</ul>
    <p><strong>Stage Two: In Progress > Getting Issues DONE</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Working -</strong> Once a bid has been accepted, the Issue will automatically set to Working status. It will remain
    there until the Developer is done with the work.</li>
    <li><strong>Functional -</strong> When the Developer is ready for their work to be functionally tested, they will commit the
    changes to their branch (no Pull Request at this point)  and set the Issue to Functional. At this step in the process, the
    Designer will test the functionality in the Developer's sandbox and then either ask for modifications or indicate their approval
    to move to Code Review.  Setting the Issue to Code Review will automatically generate a Pull Request(PR) in Github.</li>
    <li><strong>Code Review -</strong> Code Review means the new code is ready to be reviewed by another Developer. If the reviewer
    finds any problems, they are either worked out in real-time in our <a href='http://gitter.im/highfidelity/worklist' target='_blank'>Gitter</a>
    or via comments added to the Issue ticket. Once all requirements have been fulfilled, the Developer commits the code and sets the
    Issue to Completed.</li>
</ul>
    <p><strong>Stage Three: Finished > Your Issue is Done</strong></p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Completed -</strong> Once your Issue is merged into the Github Master Repository, the Developer sets the Issue to
    Completed. The Issue Designer will again be notified via email. This stage allows Designers additional time once the Issue is
    live to verify the new functionality in production. If all is good, they will move the Issue to the final status: Done!</li>
    <li><strong>Done -</strong> The Developer will not be paid until the Issue is moved into Done status. Done Issues will be picked
    up in our payment system during the next payment run via Paypal, currently twice a week.</li>
    </p>
</ul>
<h4><a name="df4">What is a reasonable bid amount?</a></h4>
<p>A bid is simply defined as the amount of money you will ask for completing the task described by an Issue write up. You can browse
through Done Issues to get a good idea of what others have charged for similar Issues. When considering an Issue, be sure to carefully
think about any problem areas or potential extra work before placing your bid, as your bid is considered an agreement between you and
Worklist for any given Issue.</strong>
</p>
<h4><a name="df5">Can I view the source code and/or download it to my own server?</a></h4>
<p>Yes! Our two main repositories, High Fidelity and Worklist are housed on <a href="https://github.com/highfidelity">Github</a>. The repositories are public and you can browse
the code there.  You can read more on the Github process in our
<a href="https://github.com/highfidelity/worklist/wiki/Using-GitHub-with-the-Worklist-Project">Worklist wiki</a>.
</p>
<h4><a name="df6">I tried to bid on an Issue and it said I am not eligible to bid, what's wrong?</a></h4>
<p>Before you can place a bid, you need to set up your payment information in your <a href='./settings'> profile settings</a>. You need to both add your Paypal address and,
if you're in the US, you will need to upload your W9 for our verification. </strong>
</p>
<h4><a name="df7">After I have completed my work, how do I get paid?</a></h4>
<p>Once you've finished work and it has had a functional and code review completed, you should set the Issue to COMPLETED.
 The project Designer will then need to verify it works in production and will then set the Issue to DONE. You will not get paid until this
 happens. Please view the <a href ="ff6"> Project Status</a> flow for more information.  All payments are
 currently handled through Paypal. When you create your worklist account, you'll be asked to supply your Paypal email address. We will pay as
 quickly as possible after a Issue is marked DONE in the worklist (this is done by the person who created or is the Designer for the Issue).</strong>

<h4><a name="df8">Who is eligible to perform code reviews?  How do I become eligible? </a></h4>
<p>Each project managed in the Worklist has it's own set of rules for Code Review eligibility.  The Project Admin
maintains these specifications. The Admin can select from the following options:</strong>
</p>
<ul>
    <li><strong>Anyone</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Anyone that is Trusted by more than 3 people</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Anyone that is Trusted by the Project Admin</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Anyone that is Trusted by the Issue Manager</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Use only code reviewers listed below</strong>(Only specific users that the Project Admin delegates)</li>
</ul>

<p>If you meet the Code Review qualifications, you will be able to start a code review by clicking the Start Code Review
button within a task.  If not, a hover message will appear over the button stating that "You are not Authorized to Code Review
this Issue".
</p>
<p>To view the guidelines for a project, navigate to the specific project from the <a href ='./projects'>
Projects page.</a>
</p>
<p>Trust generally follows completed Issues.  Therefore, if you do a really awesome job on Issues, Trust will come and so will Code Review
Eligibility!
</p>
